I"<p>In monotonic <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/logic-frameworks-formalize-truth">logics</a>, more premises means more conclusions, or at least as many. Monotonic <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/logic-frameworks-formalize-truth">logics</a> have no mechanisms for invalidating previously stated conclusions. However, real-world reasoning is punctuated with <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/natural-language-inference-derives-conceptual-structure">reasonable assumptions</a>, which can then be challenged.</p>
